WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:40.851 --> 00:00:42.879
﻿Plasma Youth Sports Games
with Unsuccess of the champion,

00:00:43.039 --> 00:00:45.233
would like to thank Slaven Bilić
for stepping in as the host.

00:00:45.367 --> 00:00:48.007
Bilić is one of the first sponsors,
ambassador and is our biggest promoter.

00:00:48.076 --> 00:00:50.677
He used his life and sports experience
in order to prepare high-quality content

00:00:50.730 --> 00:00:52.498
with his guests for all generations.
Thanks, Nane!

00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:03.895
So, Novak Đoković.
The best tennis player in history.

00:01:04.559 --> 00:01:09.860
And generally, one of the greatest
athletes of this millennium.

00:01:11.660 --> 00:01:15.380
It is a great pleasure to have you
as a guest on our show.

00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:17.860
On behalf of our entire team,
I would like to thank you

00:01:17.990 --> 00:01:21.332
for taking the time
to be a guest on our show.

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:24.260
Thank you.
Thank you for coming.

00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:29.980
I like to start the show
with current events.

00:01:30.220 --> 00:01:36.660
We had the opportunity to read
that you terminated your

00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:43.140
cooperation with Andy Murray.
-That's right. -What we...

00:01:45.100 --> 00:01:53.180
You’ve said that at the beginning
of every year, you set your priorities

00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:56.740
and goals for the upcoming season.

00:01:57.700 --> 00:02:00.540
You’ve also mentioned being
aware of your age.

00:02:00.740 --> 00:02:03.180
In advance, happy 38th birthday.

00:02:03.380 --> 00:02:06.420
Thank you. -Which you’ll
celebrate in a few days.

00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:13.700
You’ve said that this season you’d like
to enjoy the fruits of your labor

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:20.773
and find some balance between that
and the ultimate drive to win.

00:02:21.980 --> 00:02:26.500
Is that possible? -I still don’t have
an answer to that question.

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:29.660
But I'm on the path to finding that out.

00:02:30.540 --> 00:02:39.832
For me, the state I’m currently
in is somewhat new,

00:02:40.996 --> 00:02:50.025
considering that, as you mentioned,
I’ve always had and strived for clarity.

00:02:51.384 --> 00:02:57.189
In terms of setting goals, ambitions,
and knowing what I want to achieve.

00:02:57.540 --> 00:03:02.220
And I think that has helped me a lot
and the people around me as well

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:07.900
in terms of organization
and simply in life overall.

00:03:08.140 --> 00:03:12.580
And in directing energy towards
what is a priority and most important.

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:20.940
Tennis has been the primary thing
in my life for three decades.

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:27.860
It’s what I know best in life.
It’s what I do best.

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:34.460
When I became a parent
ten years ago, things changed.

00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:40.820
For the better.
I gained a new dose of motivation.

00:03:43.540 --> 00:03:48.860
I felt an even greater desire
to make my son happy,

00:03:49.100 --> 00:03:54.100
my wife, and of course
my parents always.

00:03:54.700 --> 00:03:59.260
But when I became a father,
it moved into a whole new dimension.

00:03:59.820 --> 00:04:05.940
I used that momentum -
I'm referring to my results.

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:11.900
It gave me wings, and after that,
I had a few fantastic years.

00:04:12.140 --> 00:04:16.100
And then I got injured and went
through different phases, etc.

00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:22.220
2018 was a key and decisive year
when I even considered stepping away

00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:27.060
from tennis for a while, but then
I came back and became number one.

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:30.980
But those phases both in life
and career that I went through were

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:37.100
very interesting, and that’s the approach
I take to this current time as well.

00:04:37.300 --> 00:04:41.980
I see it as just another phase.
Which is an integral part of my life.

00:04:42.180 --> 00:04:46.634
I’m putting aside the fact that I’m
a successful tennis player and athlete.

00:04:46.784 --> 00:04:50.024
And everything I’ve been
through as a professional.

00:04:50.147 --> 00:04:57.091
I see myself as a person
who has the same challenges, joys,

00:04:57.224 --> 00:05:00.264
and also problems as other people.

00:05:00.426 --> 00:05:03.346
Here, I’m talking about emotions,
not the material side of things.

00:05:03.451 --> 00:05:06.021
I understand you. -If we’re
talking about material things,

00:05:06.147 --> 00:05:08.919
I’m quite privileged,
and I’m grateful to God for that.

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:18.260
But all of us, each in our own way,
have certain challenges

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:20.660
we must face sooner or later.

00:05:21.020 --> 00:05:27.860
I’ve often, figuratively speaking,
pushed those challenges aside

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:33.060
I mean the personal, private-life ones.
I’ve often suppressed and postponed them.

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:38.980
Because you’ll understand this -
when a match is coming up,

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:42.620
when an important part
of the season is ahead,

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:49.340
you have to be in quarantine,
isolation, focused, prepared, dedicated.

00:05:49.700 --> 00:05:56.380
And just because you put something off
doesn’t mean it stays at the same intensity

00:05:56.580 --> 00:06:00.420
as when you first pushed it aside.

00:06:00.580 --> 00:06:03.380
It grows stronger by
the time you revisit it.

00:06:03.580 --> 00:06:10.860
Of course. -And that’s how some of those
problems and challenges happened to me.

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:14.580
Over time, in a kind of cascade.

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:18.660
And because of that, sooner or later,
you end up paying the price

00:06:18.860 --> 00:06:21.980
though that may be too strong a phrase.

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:29.140
You simply have to deal with
your life, and I’ve had an incredible

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:33.020
system of people around me.
As I still do today.

00:06:33.260 --> 00:06:40.190
For so many years from my wife,
my parents, my tennis team,

00:06:40.815 --> 00:06:45.620
professional staff, marketing
team, friends, and so on.

00:06:46.500 --> 00:06:52.620
I think I’ve been somewhat
cocooned. -Protected.

00:06:53.052 --> 00:06:56.496
I have several protective layers
that allow me to do what I do

00:06:56.596 --> 00:06:58.556
in the best possible way.

00:06:58.781 --> 00:07:01.781
And people around me
shield me from a lot of things.

00:07:02.209 --> 00:07:05.505
But eventually, all of that
reaches a point where...

00:07:05.677 --> 00:07:10.037
Okay, when it comes to tennis,
I still have a strong desire,

00:07:10.198 --> 00:07:13.198
I’m still here as a competitor.

00:07:13.345 --> 00:07:16.123
You asked me whether
I’m managing to find balance.

00:07:16.487 --> 00:07:23.060
I’m searching for it to such
an extent that tennis is no longer,

00:07:23.305 --> 00:07:26.063
to a large degree, my top priority.

00:07:26.177 --> 00:07:29.063
I want to be a father.
I want to be a husband.

00:07:29.242 --> 00:07:36.500
I want to make up for something
I've sacrificed because I truly have.

00:07:37.102 --> 00:07:41.164
Maybe that’s a harsh word,
but for many years,

00:07:41.420 --> 00:07:45.740
I’ve made sacrifices.
Now I feel like I want to live life.

00:07:45.980 --> 00:07:48.524
And to find, for myself,
as much as possible...

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:51.422
I don’t know how possible that is,
or what’s really possible.

00:07:51.531 --> 00:07:54.383
I’m on the path to discovering
that optimal balance.

00:07:54.527 --> 00:07:57.967
To still do what I love,
but also to be...

00:07:58.240 --> 00:08:02.080
I'll answer that in one of
your next questions.

00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:07.977
I’m not the kind of person who can
play tennis - meaning professionally -

00:08:08.150 --> 00:08:11.422
I love playing it recreationally
with friends and with my kids.

00:08:11.591 --> 00:08:14.993
But to compete professionally,
to play just for the sake of playing.

00:08:15.261 --> 00:08:17.063
I can’t do that.
-I understand you.

00:08:17.224 --> 00:08:22.624
I have to play and still feel like
I’m at that level where I could

00:08:22.910 --> 00:08:27.118
potentially win a Grand Slam
and be one of the best.

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:32.700
If that’s no longer the case,
I promised myself that would be the end.

00:08:33.180 --> 00:08:38.100
But you... You say it yourself
and I asked you about that balance.

00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:42.700
You say you’re not trained
to do anything at 99%.

00:08:42.900 --> 00:08:46.860
Only at 100%.
Is that shift the reason? -Yes.

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:50.100
Is that the reason the results
aren’t what you,

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:54.300
and we, and everyone else
have come to expect?

00:08:56.180 --> 00:08:58.660
People ask themselves
and that's a good question.

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:01.220
They think I don't train enough.

00:09:01.460 --> 00:09:05.420
You could pose the question
that way, but that’s not the truth.

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:10.700
I don’t think I’ve changed the intensity
or commitment to training.

00:09:10.940 --> 00:09:16.700
I believe that part has stayed
if not the same, then very close.

00:09:17.260 --> 00:09:29.420
I think it’s simply that I’ve made
room for other things in my focus.

00:09:29.940 --> 00:09:33.700
It sounds harsh to refer
to family as "things". -No.

00:09:33.980 --> 00:09:37.620
What I mean is, anyone who competes
at the highest level in professional sports

00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:40.940
and you can understand this,
only athletes can truly understand this.

00:09:41.140 --> 00:09:44.460
Maybe most people don’t
understand what I’m trying to say.

00:09:45.340 --> 00:09:50.180
But that level of commitment
you can even call it obsessive,

00:09:50.420 --> 00:09:56.220
you have to have it, especially
in individual sports like ours.

00:09:56.540 --> 00:10:00.100
There’s no substitution,
no postponing... -No passing the ball.

00:10:00.300 --> 00:10:03.340
You’re either present or not.
You either win or you don’t.

00:10:03.540 --> 00:10:08.780
If something goes wrong, you take
full responsibility, and that’s it.

00:10:09.180 --> 00:10:15.340
That kind of obsessive dedication
that consumed my life 24/7,

00:10:15.540 --> 00:10:17.460
I lived with it for decades.

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:22.820
By the end of 2023, which was
one of my best seasons.

00:10:24.420 --> 00:10:31.700
Of course, we all make mistakes,
but I try to live my life without regret.

00:10:31.815 --> 00:10:34.335
Because I believe that everything
happens for a reason.

00:10:34.646 --> 00:10:39.726
Still, there are moments when you
think maybe I could’ve done this

00:10:39.917 --> 00:10:41.829
a little differently.

00:10:42.170 --> 00:10:45.930
I think that happened in 2023,
after such a successful season.

00:10:46.147 --> 00:10:49.787
Which was very long and crowned
with three Grand Slam titles.

00:10:49.988 --> 00:10:54.628
Crowned with being world number
one at the age of 35, and so on.

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:59.380
I also won awards for best athlete,
and everything was beautiful.

00:10:59.583 --> 00:11:03.023
But then I simply rushed
too quickly into a new season.

00:11:04.540 --> 00:11:08.540
In tennis, for example I don’t know
how many people know this,

00:11:08.820 --> 00:11:13.460
but tennis currently has the longest
season of all global sports.

00:11:13.598 --> 00:11:15.158
There’s no break.

00:11:15.366 --> 00:11:19.966
The season officially starts
on January 1st, or even December 30th,

00:11:20.146 --> 00:11:23.026
and runs until the end of November.

00:11:23.172 --> 00:11:25.252
That basically means,
if you play the full season

00:11:25.397 --> 00:11:27.077
which I’m not doing right now.

00:11:27.237 --> 00:11:29.957
Most of the guys
and girls are playing it.

00:11:30.179 --> 00:11:32.499
For the men, the season is even
longer than for the women.

00:11:32.748 --> 00:11:36.932
They play and only have
about one month total

00:11:37.174 --> 00:11:40.300
for rest and preparation
for the next season.

00:11:40.580 --> 00:11:47.707
I committed too early to playing
the start of the 2024 season.

00:11:47.831 --> 00:11:49.591
At that time, I was training
with Goran Ivanišević.

00:11:49.682 --> 00:11:51.242
He was my coach.

00:11:51.460 --> 00:11:55.199
I remember he didn’t agree
with that decision.

00:11:55.429 --> 00:11:58.715
He wanted me to play something
right before the Australian Open

00:11:58.895 --> 00:12:05.676
at the beginning of 2024
but considering how intense

00:12:05.873 --> 00:12:09.113
the end of my season was,
he was right.

00:12:09.500 --> 00:12:13.277
I think it would have been better
if I had rested, started training again,

00:12:13.389 --> 00:12:15.149
and then gone straight there.

00:12:15.264 --> 00:12:17.784
Played one or two warm-up matches
and gone directly to the Grand Slam.

00:12:17.898 --> 00:12:21.338
But I chose to play
at the United Cup.

00:12:21.617 --> 00:12:26.684
I played for the Serbian national team.
We rarely get the opportunity

00:12:26.925 --> 00:12:30.734
to participate in team tournaments.

00:12:30.968 --> 00:12:34.728
Our biggest is the Davis Cup.
Then we have the United Cup, etc.

00:12:35.241 --> 00:12:39.401
It was interesting for me to go there
because of the camaraderie and atmosphere.

00:12:39.649 --> 00:12:46.301
I’ve always missed that team spirit.
However, it was too much.

00:12:46.465 --> 00:12:48.940
We played the first match
on December 30th.

00:12:49.136 --> 00:12:52.736
And I had finished the previous
season on December 1st.

00:12:52.913 --> 00:12:56.411
I had less than four weeks
to rest and prepare.

00:12:57.065 --> 00:13:02.755
That’s one example of a decision
I could’ve made differently.

00:13:02.997 --> 00:13:06.957
But I didn’t. It’s okay.
It happened for a reason.

00:13:07.103 --> 00:13:12.974
And then came the burnout.
I didn’t have time to rest and recharge.

00:13:13.302 --> 00:13:16.488
I immediately jumped
into another Grand Slam.

00:13:16.989 --> 00:13:20.669
I reached the semifinals
and lost to Jannik Sinner.

00:13:20.927 --> 00:13:23.817
That day, I was only
physically present on the court.

00:13:24.134 --> 00:13:27.134
Physically there, but mentally
completely absent.

00:13:27.506 --> 00:13:31.506
After that, I realized
I had no more energy.

00:13:31.798 --> 00:13:34.798
Not just for that tournament,
but more broadly.

00:13:35.038 --> 00:13:37.817
I kept playing afterward,
trying to find myself again.

00:13:37.996 --> 00:13:41.029
I thought after playing one or two
tournaments I’d get into form.

00:13:41.218 --> 00:13:46.110
Then I started finding myself
in other things as well business,

00:13:46.377 --> 00:13:50.805
and some other activities
where I feel more fulfillment

00:13:50.954 --> 00:13:56.074
while doing them. Then I asked
myself a question, and I still ask it:

00:13:56.294 --> 00:14:00.214
Have I earned the right to ask myself
why do I continue doing this?

00:14:00.429 --> 00:14:10.989
And do I still find joy and
satisfaction in doing what I do?

00:14:11.645 --> 00:14:15.965
After everything I’ve accomplished.
History will always be there.

00:14:16.204 --> 00:14:20.644
There’s always a plan: "Just this next
tournament, then that one."

00:14:20.812 --> 00:14:26.645
A historical stat, I’ll break one more
record my own or someone else’s.

00:14:26.903 --> 00:14:28.716
That will always be there.

00:14:28.841 --> 00:14:31.231
And thank God I’ve
put myself in that position.

00:14:31.460 --> 00:14:33.900
But what’s the purpose?

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:38.100
Because if I don’t enjoy being
on the court and we can’t

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:40.340
always enjoy it
you know how it is.

00:14:40.580 --> 00:14:43.660
You struggle every day,
you don’t want to get out of bed,

00:14:43.820 --> 00:14:47.140
but you force yourself
to train, run, and so on.

00:14:47.580 --> 00:14:52.140
Do I still find fulfillment
in doing this?

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:55.620
Do I still push myself
through each season?

00:14:55.860 --> 00:14:58.860
Am I forcing myself to do this,
or am I doing it because deep down,

00:14:58.998 --> 00:15:02.495
I feel passion and love
for competition?

00:15:02.630 --> 00:15:04.589
That’s the real philosophy.

00:15:05.128 --> 00:15:10.008
That’s the issue with modern
professional sports - especially

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:13.700
the ones where a lot of money
is involved.

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:16.580
In football, for example,
they play over 80 matches a year.

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:19.020
The season has been
extended massively.

00:15:19.380 --> 00:15:23.500
Now they’ve invented
the Club World Cup,

00:15:23.700 --> 00:15:27.720
and players won’t even
have time to rest or prepare.

00:15:28.135 --> 00:15:33.180
That’s a problem for everyone because
it’s all become too big a business.

00:15:33.420 --> 00:15:36.500
We’ll talk more about that later.

00:15:37.277 --> 00:15:43.820
Even though a lot has already been said,
let’s go back to the early ’90s

00:15:46.246 --> 00:15:49.100
to that famous meeting
with Jelena Genčić.

00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:53.180
You were 4.5 years old,
and you were on Mount Kopaonik.

00:15:53.334 --> 00:15:56.337
You come from a sporting family.
But your father always said

00:15:56.434 --> 00:15:58.305
you preferred skiing.
-That’s right.

00:15:58.429 --> 00:16:00.349
So where did your love
for tennis come from?

00:16:00.645 --> 00:16:04.525
Destiny. I don’t know
how else to explain it.

00:16:04.858 --> 00:16:09.961
I was four years old.
We grew up in Belgrade.

00:16:10.084 --> 00:16:13.009
I have two younger brothers.
And we spent a lot of time

00:16:13.167 --> 00:16:16.407
on Mount Kopaonik,
which is in southern Serbia,

00:16:16.603 --> 00:16:22.829
because that’s where my parents met
and started their hospitality business,

00:16:23.585 --> 00:16:25.805
which we lived off.

00:16:26.980 --> 00:16:31.580
They also had some work in Belgrade,
but it wasn’t as financially stable

00:16:31.820 --> 00:16:35.540
as the income from
the restaurant on Kopaonik.

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:41.940
But even that business was seasonal.
Sometimes, during the war-torn ’90s,

00:16:42.180 --> 00:16:46.300
the seasons were actually better
than in the early 2000s.

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:50.380
And at that time,
because of the foreigners,

00:16:50.580 --> 00:16:53.940
and the long winters and summers,
it was possible to make a living from it.

00:16:54.700 --> 00:16:58.740
And, well, by chance, although
I don't believe in coincidences,

00:16:58.980 --> 00:17:04.020
but let's just say it was fate,
life arranged it in such a way

00:17:04.189 --> 00:17:08.589
that three tennis courts
were being built near the restaurant.

00:17:08.703 --> 00:17:10.583
I mean, just 50 meters away.

00:17:10.769 --> 00:17:14.508
Up until then, I think my father had
watched maybe three matches in his life.

00:17:14.805 --> 00:17:19.125
He watched those legends who used to
play back then, and that was it.

00:17:19.980 --> 00:17:23.700
He watched Borg, McEnroe,
Becker, and that was it.

00:17:23.940 --> 00:17:27.940
But he had no real contact with tennis,
neither he nor my mother.

00:17:28.180 --> 00:17:34.580
My mom graduated from
the sports faculty here in Belgrade,

00:17:35.100 --> 00:17:39.060
and my father was a professional
football player for a while,

00:17:39.380 --> 00:17:43.740
but he mostly focused on skiing.
Then he became a skiing instructor,

00:17:43.822 --> 00:17:47.596
and that's how they met. She had fallen
on the slope, and he came to help,

00:17:47.682 --> 00:17:49.635
so he said: "You need an instructor,"

00:17:50.580 --> 00:17:54.660
and little by little, I showed up after
9 months. But it's an interesting story,

00:17:54.862 --> 00:17:58.342
and that mountain, Kopaonik,
is very special to all of us.

00:17:58.740 --> 00:18:03.580
And I was just a kid, of course curious.
I must have been four or five years old.

00:18:03.820 --> 00:18:09.801
It was 1992 and I was watching
them build the courts,

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:13.820
bringing the workers beer
from the restaurant,

00:18:14.140 --> 00:18:19.060
and they let me mix a bit of plaster.
It was interesting to me.

00:18:20.500 --> 00:18:27.649
When they finished building everything,
the first tennis camp started. I joined.

00:18:27.843 --> 00:18:31.235
Jelena Genčić wasn't there
at that camp, she came later.

00:18:31.356 --> 00:18:35.276
In that first camp, there were
a lot of kids. It was summer.

00:18:35.525 --> 00:18:40.445
My parents asked
if I could play there, and I did.

00:18:40.780 --> 00:18:43.700
That's when the first video was made,
with the colorful racket

00:18:43.900 --> 00:18:48.216
and the tongue sticking out,
and that was my first backhand.

00:18:49.095 --> 00:18:55.375
Then, not long after, Jelena Genčić
came, maybe later that summer,

00:18:55.780 --> 00:18:57.860
and I spent a bit of time with her.

00:18:58.220 --> 00:19:03.900
And that's when I started playing
tennis, in camps, for 2 or 3 years.

00:19:04.540 --> 00:19:07.060
I instantly fell in love with it.

00:19:07.500 --> 00:19:12.220
I asked my dad if he could buy me
a racket, and he bought me soft balls

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:16.500
and a small racket,
and I was hitting the wall all day.

00:19:16.808 --> 00:19:19.648
And of course,
I was watching matches...

00:19:19.902 --> 00:19:30.194
My first exposure to a tennis match on
TV was in 1992, the final with Sampras.

00:19:30.820 --> 00:19:33.260
I can't quite remember exactly
who he beat in the final,

00:19:33.500 --> 00:19:40.054
but it was his first Wimbledon win. And
that's when I said: "This is my idol."

00:19:40.665 --> 00:19:47.018
It was probably because he was
the first one I saw, and I liked it.

00:19:47.456 --> 00:19:55.325
Even though my game and style
are completely different from his.

00:19:57.458 --> 00:20:04.403
So, I started playing and it
became a continuous thing.

00:20:04.624 --> 00:20:07.379
However, I was so young and small.

00:20:07.579 --> 00:20:13.939
At the time I also skied, played
football, started school, and so on.

00:20:14.380 --> 00:20:21.060
It wasn't really yet professional.
Then there was Jelena Genčić...

00:20:22.044 --> 00:20:31.474
She was known in the former Yugoslavia
for her extraordinary eye for talent.

00:20:33.220 --> 00:20:37.300
Maybe there were a few people
like that: Niki Pilić, Jelena Genčić...

00:20:37.660 --> 00:20:40.780
Did she discover
Monika Seleš as well?

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:46.100
Yes, Monika Seleš, who lived and grew up
in Novi Sad, and then moved to America.

00:20:46.266 --> 00:20:49.485
Jelena also worked with her.
I knew everything about Monika,

00:20:49.660 --> 00:20:53.620
when she ate, slept, what she did,
what she listened to, what she read...

00:20:53.980 --> 00:21:00.180
So, for me, Monika was my first
real idol, my role model, so to speak.

00:21:00.820 --> 00:21:05.660
I felt closer to her because
she worked with Jelena.

00:21:05.900 --> 00:21:10.380
And then, Jelena would take me
to her house. My parents allowed it,

00:21:11.180 --> 00:21:17.820
they collaborated with Jelena,
who I like to call my "tennis mother".

00:21:19.260 --> 00:21:21.950
I was around 8 or 9 years old.
We would go to her house,

00:21:22.145 --> 00:21:26.387
listen to classical music,
read poetry, watch...

00:21:26.544 --> 00:21:30.176
We did visualization exercises that she
didn't call "visualization" back then.

00:21:30.303 --> 00:21:32.645
The same visualization
that's famous today.

00:21:32.767 --> 00:21:37.035
You close your eyes, visualize what you
want, and believe it will come true.

00:21:37.377 --> 00:21:40.148
She told me:
"Just close your eyes."

00:21:40.632 --> 00:21:46.913
We would watch videos of players like
Edberg, Becker, Agassi, Sampras, Goran,

00:21:47.580 --> 00:21:52.980
Monika, Capriati,
Steffi Graf, and so on...

00:21:55.740 --> 00:21:58.745
We would watch them,
and then she'd ask me:

00:21:58.903 --> 00:22:02.049
"Alright, you just watched Becker.
What did you see in his game?"

00:22:02.257 --> 00:22:06.518
I was nine years old. I'd tell her:
"He had an outstanding serve."

00:22:06.663 --> 00:22:11.143
She'd say: "Yes, an excellent serve. But
what exactly did you see in the serve?"

00:22:11.321 --> 00:22:14.321
And then she'd provoke me
to say exactly what I saw,

00:22:14.553 --> 00:22:20.633
whether it was precision,
power, spin, position, whatever...

00:22:20.810 --> 00:22:24.770
She'd provoke me like that,
and in doing so, she taught me

00:22:25.053 --> 00:22:29.756
to watch tennis professionally,
to see it the way it should be seen,

00:22:29.860 --> 00:22:34.540
so I could absorb all those elements
and then apply them to my game.

00:22:34.780 --> 00:22:40.340
And that's where the imitations came
from in the first part of my career.

00:22:40.580 --> 00:22:44.380
I imitated each of them, because I
became so immersed in it all

00:22:44.580 --> 00:22:49.930
that I really wanted to have Agassi's
return, Becker's serve, Goran's serve,

00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:53.500
Goran's racket breaking,
or whatever it was...

00:22:53.740 --> 00:22:58.700
Yes... And you know what is fascinating
here? Correct me if I'm wrong...

00:22:59.020 --> 00:23:03.420
The woman you're talking about,
the one you call your tennis mother.

00:23:04.220 --> 00:23:10.060
From a coach's perspective,
her methods are fascinating to me.

00:23:10.300 --> 00:23:14.700
All of these... You yourself said
that a child has to dream. -Yes.

00:23:16.780 --> 00:23:23.740
Classical music, poetry, languages...
How will you approach the queen?

00:23:23.940 --> 00:23:29.460
Not if you win, but when you win
Wimbledon. Raising cardboard trophies...

00:23:29.700 --> 00:23:35.020
To me, that's... You know, these phrases
today, and in the last 20 years,

00:23:35.260 --> 00:23:41.100
"'nothing is impossible", "the sky's
the limit", "breaking barriers",

00:23:41.620 --> 00:23:46.340
you guys were doing all of that through
play because you were training for it.

00:23:46.453 --> 00:23:48.636
She trained you, your dreams.

00:23:48.759 --> 00:23:52.636
Not "if something happens",
but "when it happens".

00:23:52.829 --> 00:23:56.309
When you win Wimbledon, you have to
dress this way, you have to say this...

00:23:56.454 --> 00:23:58.526
When the queen arrives,
you have to do this...

00:23:58.684 --> 00:24:03.433
That's incredible! A method
for the chosen ones, for champions.

00:24:03.564 --> 00:24:06.284
It's not for everyone,
of course, because it's not...

00:24:06.425 --> 00:24:09.097
Yes, and that's exactly
what stands out.

00:24:09.240 --> 00:24:13.948
She had that eye,
she could see in me not just talent,

00:24:14.060 --> 00:24:17.220
but the qualities,
exactly what you explained,

00:24:17.460 --> 00:24:25.460
that I could hear it, realize it, take
it in, adopt it, and apply it tomorrow.

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:30.180
And that I truly believed in it, that it
wasn't just something I did because

00:24:30.310 --> 00:24:33.748
an authority figure, whether
it was a parent or coach-told me to,

00:24:33.941 --> 00:24:38.856
but because I believed in it with every
part of myself, with every cell,

00:24:38.998 --> 00:24:41.009
and that would shape my future.

00:24:41.620 --> 00:24:48.780
Now, your story sounds like a movie,
as if everything went by smoothly.

00:24:49.540 --> 00:24:56.260
But it was the early '90s, a time of
war, later sanctions against Serbia,

00:24:56.381 --> 00:24:59.462
and other issues that were present.

00:24:59.860 --> 00:25:03.500
Then comes a woman
who tells your parents,

00:25:03.820 --> 00:25:10.900
while you're just four and a half
years old, that your son has talent,

00:25:11.180 --> 00:25:15.940
that it's a gift from the heavens, and
that your son will be in the top ten

00:25:16.063 --> 00:25:18.023
by the time he is 17 years old.

00:25:18.380 --> 00:25:23.980
You said your parents
didn't only have financial problems...

00:25:24.260 --> 00:25:30.500
For someone who knew nothing about this,
who didn't know who to pick out...

00:25:30.843 --> 00:25:35.483
Your father was the provider,
the one who provides for the family.

00:25:36.260 --> 00:25:41.940
But at that time, it was an individual
sport, an expensive sport.

00:25:42.420 --> 00:25:46.380
Objectively, your father
lacked the logistics.

00:25:46.700 --> 00:25:50.260
For all of us, our fathers are the ones
who took us to our first training,

00:25:50.580 --> 00:25:56.420
to our first match, but for you,
he probably also had the role

00:25:56.700 --> 00:26:03.420
of agent in the beginning,
part-coach, and so on...

00:26:03.820 --> 00:26:07.380
It's a complex relationship
between you and him,

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:13.140
which later, once you're recognized
and experts step into those roles,

00:26:13.420 --> 00:26:20.780
returns to that father-son dynamic.
That's difficult. It's complex.

00:26:20.943 --> 00:26:25.393
Well, it's complex, you know...

00:26:26.340 --> 00:26:33.534
I mean, if we had known at that time
that all of this would happen,

00:26:35.140 --> 00:26:37.660
and that everything would be achieved,

00:26:37.860 --> 00:26:40.448
I think we would have,
of course, agreed to it.

00:26:40.621 --> 00:26:43.181
It's what both he and I
desperately wanted.

00:26:43.585 --> 00:26:48.425
And of course, my mother, who wasn't
at the front lines in that sense,

00:26:48.940 --> 00:26:53.020
but she was the one who held the family
together. -You say she was the pillar.

00:26:53.260 --> 00:26:56.900
She was the pillar, without her,
it would have been complete chaos.

00:26:57.500 --> 00:27:02.740
She held us 4 men together, my 2 younger
brothers and of course, my father.

00:27:03.060 --> 00:27:05.860
Everyone was into sports, changing
a lot of clothes, went to school,

00:27:06.060 --> 00:27:09.380
she had to clean a lot
and prepare things for us.

00:27:09.580 --> 00:27:13.340
I mean, a lot of women do that,
thank God, but on the other hand,

00:27:13.540 --> 00:27:20.262
most of them have a lot of difficulties
keeping the family together

00:27:21.620 --> 00:27:25.540
while allowing the men in the house,

00:27:25.820 --> 00:27:31.420
like in her case, to live
their dreams outside the home.

00:27:33.980 --> 00:27:38.540
Because of that, I have to mention
my mother as the pillar of the family,

00:27:38.780 --> 00:27:49.220
and my father as the driving force. He
was the energy I needed at that moment

00:27:50.060 --> 00:27:59.640
because there were a few moments
early in my life where I was uncertain

00:27:59.805 --> 00:28:05.205
about whether tennis was the right
choice. I loved skiing a lot.

00:28:06.220 --> 00:28:09.812
And of course, as a son and a little
boy, you look up to your father...

00:28:09.999 --> 00:28:12.625
Your father is your first role model,

00:28:12.804 --> 00:28:15.444
the first example of what
you want to be in life.

00:28:15.512 --> 00:28:18.452
When I looked at videos
and pictures of him skiing,

00:28:18.585 --> 00:28:23.117
or of the times when he taught me to
ski, I naturally wanted to be like him.

00:28:23.240 --> 00:28:25.600
Why wouldn't I want to be like my dad?

00:28:25.779 --> 00:28:30.460
And of course, he wanted to support me,
in anything, but he gave me a choice.

00:28:30.696 --> 00:28:32.921
Both he and my mom
gave me the choice.

00:28:33.121 --> 00:28:38.796
I remember those moments as very
defining, very prominent in my life.

00:28:40.015 --> 00:28:45.655
I was about ten years old,
we were in Belgrade.

00:28:46.060 --> 00:28:49.860
Since we had changed apartments so many
times during that time in the late '90s,

00:28:50.100 --> 00:28:53.921
along with the bombing,
we didn't have a permanent home.

00:28:54.228 --> 00:28:57.765
And there were a lot of difficulties
for them, as you mentioned.

00:28:58.043 --> 00:29:00.577
Tennis was an incredibly
expensive sport.

00:29:00.769 --> 00:29:03.809
It still is today, and especially
back then. They simply...

00:29:04.104 --> 00:29:08.587
I remember my dad putting
10 Marks on the table and saying,

00:29:08.757 --> 00:29:10.290
"This is all we have."

00:29:10.443 --> 00:29:14.516
At that moment, something inside me
awakened, that fatherly instinct in me,

00:29:14.727 --> 00:29:20.634
that I had to grow up at 12 years old.
I simply understood his message.

00:29:22.020 --> 00:29:27.660
But despite everything, he was ready to
do whatever it took to support me, 100%,

00:29:27.980 --> 00:29:31.020
and said: "We'll find the money,
we'll create the conditions,

00:29:31.260 --> 00:29:35.558
we'll figure it out. If there's no clear
path right now, we'll make one.

00:29:36.340 --> 00:29:39.180
You just have to tell me,
are you ready for this?

00:29:39.460 --> 00:29:44.420
Do you fully want to dedicate
yourself to this?"

00:29:47.249 --> 00:29:50.049
For a ten-year-old, that was
a huge thing. -For a kid...

00:29:50.259 --> 00:29:59.265
I wanted to play, I loved skiing,
I loved football, and I loved tennis.

00:29:59.808 --> 00:30:03.734
And then, I think in the end,
the choice was the right one.

00:30:03.940 --> 00:30:09.101
I mean, definitely... And full of fate.
But at that moment, it was a little...

00:30:09.356 --> 00:30:15.296
He said: "Son, sleep on it, think
about it. If tomorrow, in your heart,

00:30:15.408 --> 00:30:17.937
you feel that tennis is the one,
we'll go for it."

00:30:18.094 --> 00:30:20.539
So, I'm here, we're all going together?
-We're all going together.

00:30:20.682 --> 00:30:26.332
That's incredible. And you've already
mentioned your mother as the pillar.

00:30:26.577 --> 00:30:32.577
So, a woman who, just like the
relationship between you and your dad,

00:30:32.699 --> 00:30:35.619
which isn't just father and son,
has to make sure that

00:30:35.825 --> 00:30:39.435
the most important relationship
isn't lost, and at the same time,

00:30:39.593 --> 00:30:42.420
you have, as you said,
two younger brothers?

00:30:42.689 --> 00:30:48.099
All of that has to be managed,
without any script.

00:30:48.304 --> 00:30:52.224
They didn't know anything. Back then,
there wasn't even a film about this,

00:30:52.417 --> 00:30:55.497
where you could see that
this is how things would unfold,

00:30:55.727 --> 00:30:59.647
how other fathers did things.
It was all new, with so many challenges,

00:30:59.792 --> 00:31:02.900
so many unpredictable difficulties,
making it easy to fall into problems.

00:31:03.905 --> 00:31:09.098
Did you, and I asked Goran this as well,
since he comes from the same sport,

00:31:09.682 --> 00:31:20.547
did you ever feel that you
just had to succeed? -Yes.

00:31:21.100 --> 00:31:25.140
You had to, because of the future,
the existence... -100%.

00:31:25.239 --> 00:31:27.404
It's not about
"Do we want to go on vacation?"

00:31:27.500 --> 00:31:29.780
or "Do we want to afford some luxury?"

00:31:29.894 --> 00:31:33.038
It's the existence of the whole family,
not just yours. -100%.

00:31:33.233 --> 00:31:37.686
It all depends on you. And that's
incredibly hard for a child.

00:31:37.848 --> 00:31:42.688
100%, as you said. That's absolutely how
it was. That's what I mentioned earlier,

00:31:42.905 --> 00:31:47.991
when I was 12, and that scene
happened with those 10 Marks,

00:31:48.180 --> 00:31:53.131
that was when I really woke up,
"OK, this is it". -At 12, you grew up...

00:31:53.382 --> 00:31:58.405
I had to grow up, skip six years,
and become an adult.

00:31:59.192 --> 00:32:03.812
I had to take responsibility,
help out at home wherever I could,

00:32:04.156 --> 00:32:09.326
within our little family ecosystem,
figuring out how I could contribute.

00:32:09.540 --> 00:32:18.540
I realized that my role, at that moment,
was to take care of my younger brothers,

00:32:19.660 --> 00:32:23.796
which felt logical and natural.
That was the first thing.

00:32:23.946 --> 00:32:28.609
The second thing, the bigger
and more challenging part

00:32:28.897 --> 00:32:34.031
that would bring results in the future,
but we didn't know this at the time,

00:32:34.514 --> 00:32:39.394
was that I had to fully dedicate
myself to my tennis life.

00:32:39.940 --> 00:32:42.940
When I say "tennis life", I don't
just mean tennis training and such,

00:32:43.140 --> 00:32:47.591
but everything I did had to be
absolutely dedicated to that.

00:32:48.300 --> 00:32:54.660
And what was remarkable
and helped me a lot,

00:32:54.900 --> 00:32:59.380
though it was very hard
and challenging,

00:32:59.620 --> 00:33:04.140
was that all family members devoted
themselves to my tennis life.

00:33:05.060 --> 00:33:13.020
That hurts my father and mother,
but also my two younger brothers

00:33:13.300 --> 00:33:16.789
where neglected,
especially the middle brother.

00:33:16.952 --> 00:33:22.803
The youngest showed it,
he played tennis six hours a day.

00:33:23.151 --> 00:33:27.735
Both were talented.
Our parents lacked strength.

00:33:28.055 --> 00:33:31.531
At that time, as it was,
no money, no resources...

00:33:31.768 --> 00:33:36.633
This is absolutely not a critique.
No, it's just the truth,

00:33:36.843 --> 00:33:40.763
and they themselves know
and admit it, and so on.

00:33:40.980 --> 00:33:45.340
It was a tough reality
for both my brothers,

00:33:45.540 --> 00:33:50.260
especially my middle brother Marko.
He's still in tennis,

00:33:50.460 --> 00:33:53.900
he's also doing other things,
but he's still a tennis coach.

00:33:54.100 --> 00:33:56.540
That's how much he loves it.
The youngest isn't.

00:33:56.740 --> 00:34:00.580
He's in other areas,
but Marko really loves tennis.

00:34:00.780 --> 00:34:06.020
He always wanted to succeed.

00:34:07.140 --> 00:34:18.293
Even though being Novak’s brothers
brought them some privileges,

00:34:20.549 --> 00:34:23.629
they also lived in the shadow.
When you live in the shadow...

00:34:23.860 --> 00:34:29.700
Good thing you're the eldest brother.
-Yes. -You're their idol.

00:34:30.100 --> 00:34:32.620
My older brother was my idol too.

00:34:34.540 --> 00:34:38.380
Is it the same in other sports?

00:34:38.660 --> 00:34:43.860
Parents have to support
and give things up.

00:34:46.420 --> 00:34:50.380
But in tennis it can go
to the edge of survival.

00:34:50.660 --> 00:34:54.100
That's how it was for Goran,
for example.

00:34:54.340 --> 00:34:59.940
Have you talked to legends from other
countries? Is it the same there?

00:35:00.205 --> 00:35:04.386
Of course support is needed,
like with Nadal, for instance.

00:35:04.532 --> 00:35:07.347
A teammate pushes you forward.

00:35:08.540 --> 00:35:12.500
Is it easier to afford that
in other countries?

00:35:12.740 --> 00:35:16.759
You mean in tennis,
for colleagues in the sport?

00:35:18.260 --> 00:35:21.033
Yes, but not to this extent.

00:35:23.220 --> 00:35:26.260
You mentioned Nadal,
he comes from Spain,

00:35:27.220 --> 00:35:34.140
a country with big tennis tradition,
a strong tennis federation.

00:35:34.900 --> 00:35:39.067
They have a broad system,

00:35:39.700 --> 00:35:46.165
even the smallest village
has access to tennis courts.

00:35:46.940 --> 00:35:49.300
Tennis is a national sport there.

00:35:49.660 --> 00:35:54.296
That’s why they’ve produced
so many great players.

00:35:54.484 --> 00:35:56.564
Much respect for that.

00:35:57.085 --> 00:36:03.460
Then there’s France, and so on.
Tennis is a Western sport.

00:36:03.829 --> 00:36:09.029
It began on French courts
in the 16th century,

00:36:09.620 --> 00:36:16.100
and became more professional
in late 19th century England.

00:36:16.380 --> 00:36:18.900
It then spread from there.

00:36:19.260 --> 00:36:23.180
It was always a sport of the elite,
the "white" sport, as they say.

00:36:24.100 --> 00:36:29.780
That’s why most top players
come from such countries.

00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:35.580
When small nations show up,
people ask, what are these guys

00:36:35.780 --> 00:36:39.820
from Serbia or Croatia doing here?
Who are they, what are they?

00:36:40.038 --> 00:36:44.040
It bothers some people.
You can feel it.

00:36:44.190 --> 00:36:46.462
Not just in tennis,
but in other sports too.

00:36:46.632 --> 00:36:48.672
But tennis is what I know best.

00:36:49.580 --> 00:36:59.620
At 12, you went to Munich,
to Niki Pilić, right? -Yes.

00:36:59.860 --> 00:37:04.660
But I wanted to ask,
along with Munich and Kopaonik,

00:37:04.860 --> 00:37:09.780
you had a normal childhood, right?
You had your neighborhood.

00:37:10.340 --> 00:37:14.980
You often mention your grandfather
as an important figure.

00:37:15.500 --> 00:37:17.820
You had friends,
you went to school.

00:37:18.020 --> 00:37:23.540
Only in high school, as your mom said,
there was no understanding for your sport.

00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:28.420
But you had your group,
your neighborhood, your court.

00:37:28.660 --> 00:37:34.580
How did you handle puberty
and adolescence?

00:37:34.860 --> 00:37:38.620
The good and the bad?
Like staying out late,

00:37:38.860 --> 00:37:42.361
falling in love, cigarettes, alcohol?

00:37:45.700 --> 00:37:51.820
I think I mostly skipped that.
Both luckily and unluckily. -Yes.

00:37:52.340 --> 00:38:00.540
Luckily, it gave me a clean,
clear path toward my goal.

00:38:00.780 --> 00:38:05.660
It wasn’t hard for me
to give those things up.

00:38:05.940 --> 00:38:11.189
I didn’t even see it as sacrifice.
This was just what I wanted.

00:38:11.467 --> 00:38:17.759
Through tennis I had
my circle, my community,

00:38:18.340 --> 00:38:24.300
but not to the extent most kids had.
Yes, I missed a lot,

00:38:24.540 --> 00:38:31.180
as anyone does who...
...chooses a pro sports career

00:38:31.500 --> 00:38:37.180
in their teenage years, when you are
already labeled as ultra-talented

00:38:37.420 --> 00:38:48.300
and seen as a big prospect.
So at 12 and a half, nearly 13,

00:38:48.700 --> 00:38:54.980
I went to Niki. At that time, Niki's academy
didn’t accept anyone under 14.

00:38:55.340 --> 00:39:02.540
It was one of the top 2 or 3
academies in Europe, top 5 in the world.

00:39:04.420 --> 00:39:08.740
Jelena Genčić was close with Niki.
They knew each other well,

00:39:08.980 --> 00:39:17.180
they were friends and collaborators.
One day, Jelena told my parents,

00:39:17.540 --> 00:39:23.470
she had given all she could,
shared all her knowledge.

00:39:23.663 --> 00:39:27.595
She said I was ready
for a new chapter,

00:39:27.880 --> 00:39:34.174
that it was time to find
a new team, coach, environment.

00:39:35.620 --> 00:39:39.780
That says a lot about
who she was as a person.

00:39:39.980 --> 00:39:45.380
You know, in coaching, how hard it is...
I was never a coach,

00:39:45.629 --> 00:39:48.448
but hope to get to know that someday.

00:39:48.710 --> 00:39:53.074
Still, from my view,
it’s very hard to step away

00:39:53.200 --> 00:39:57.113
from a super talented kid and say,
"I’ve done enough."

00:39:57.324 --> 00:40:01.238
That’s a big step
for anyone’s ego and pride.

00:40:01.446 --> 00:40:04.918
To say, "Go to someone else,
I’ve given you what I can."

00:40:05.171 --> 00:40:11.105
That’s a huge thing. It speaks to
her humility and her character.

00:40:11.441 --> 00:40:15.621
She called Niki and said,
I know you don’t take kids under 14,

00:40:15.910 --> 00:40:20.350
but this kid is special.
Please, take him for a week or two.

00:40:20.620 --> 00:40:23.980
See what he's like, feel him out.

00:40:24.220 --> 00:40:29.460
If you think he’s not good enough
or not mature enough, send him back.

00:40:30.140 --> 00:40:33.380
But try it. -I believe he's the one.

00:40:33.617 --> 00:40:39.830
Both Niki and Jelena
highlight your approach.

00:40:41.140 --> 00:40:45.740
Niki says Novak never forgets
anything I told him.

00:40:45.980 --> 00:40:49.940
Jelena says the same
about your mindset.

00:40:51.260 --> 00:40:55.900
How do you remember Pilić,
who raised you back then?

00:40:56.220 --> 00:41:06.540
Before I answer that, I just want to
mention the moment that was crucial,

00:41:07.740 --> 00:41:10.770
that shaped my life
and my family's life.

00:41:10.893 --> 00:41:13.213
That was when I was 12 and a half,
during the bombing,

00:41:13.312 --> 00:41:15.630
when they put 10 Marks on the table.

00:41:15.940 --> 00:41:20.860
I think that’s when I realized
I had to grow up in that moment,

00:41:21.100 --> 00:41:25.980
take responsibility,
and accept nothing but success.

00:41:26.180 --> 00:41:29.380
Like you said, and that’s 100% true.

00:41:29.580 --> 00:41:35.380
In my head, I felt a clear message
to myself, probably from above too,

00:41:35.700 --> 00:41:41.180
but also from those around me:
It’s on you now.

00:41:41.420 --> 00:41:47.140
Of course I’d have support, but it was
on me to devote all my energy to it.

00:41:47.420 --> 00:41:52.300
And if I did that, I deeply felt
success was guaranteed.

00:41:52.580 --> 00:41:57.460
Of course, nothing in life is 100%,
but when you just feel it...

00:41:57.700 --> 00:42:03.546
To answer your question,
that mindset we spoke of,

00:42:03.905 --> 00:42:12.460
I think that moment shaped my mindset,
my ability to absorb and adopt.

00:42:13.660 --> 00:42:19.460
Like my father says:
you have to breathe, eat, drink tennis.

00:42:20.580 --> 00:42:27.900
That’s how I lived for many years.
Especially during those teenage years.

00:42:28.500 --> 00:42:37.500
There was nothing else. Just that.
That unusual, extreme dedication.

00:42:39.020 --> 00:42:45.020
When I went to Niki, I was fully aware
of what I’d just said,

00:42:45.300 --> 00:42:50.860
that Niki was a legend, that his academy
was one of the best worldwide,

00:42:51.180 --> 00:42:56.922
that Goran, Becker,
and others came there,

00:42:57.468 --> 00:43:02.548
that very few players
had access at all.

00:43:04.340 --> 00:43:10.761
I know Jelena Genčić used up
her favor just to call him.

00:43:11.035 --> 00:43:17.900
That means, looking back now,
use the chance.

00:43:18.140 --> 00:43:24.540
No one had to say it. It was clear.
-But you were 12. -You know, yes,

00:43:25.380 --> 00:43:31.460
but I was forced to mature fast.
-That’s why you’re Đoković. -Yes,

00:43:31.860 --> 00:43:35.180
but when I came, I...

00:43:36.620 --> 00:43:42.375
I did feel a bit more pressure,
in terms of expectations,

00:43:42.788 --> 00:43:46.953
but I also couldn’t wait
to change my environment.

00:43:47.389 --> 00:43:52.195
There was war here, bombs falling,
so many horrible things.

00:43:52.599 --> 00:43:57.559
As much as I love my country,
I wanted a change.

00:43:58.020 --> 00:44:05.140
To see if that would inspire me,
give me new motivation, a push forward.

00:44:05.540 --> 00:44:10.180
I went to a fantastic place,
the best possible one for me then.

00:44:10.420 --> 00:44:12.900
Jelena was completely right.

00:44:13.220 --> 00:44:18.820
Niki’s wife Mia and Niki himself
accepted me like a son.

00:44:19.260 --> 00:44:23.500
I’m grateful to them
until the grave, as they say.

00:44:26.060 --> 00:44:32.900
Not because I was theirs,
or from their region... I don’t know.

00:44:33.180 --> 00:44:38.580
There were others like me. A few
Croats, some from Serbia, but very few.

00:44:38.820 --> 00:44:41.700
Most were foreigners.

00:44:42.020 --> 00:44:48.780
They just... I tried to be everything
my parents raised me to be:

00:44:49.820 --> 00:44:56.900
a polite boy, normal, humble,
hardworking, there with a purpose.

00:44:57.460 --> 00:45:01.780
To value everything I was given
or allowed to do.

00:45:02.140 --> 00:45:06.740
And when I got the chancem
to show myself. Then that chance came.

00:45:06.909 --> 00:45:08.914
I played, Niki watched me.

00:45:09.224 --> 00:45:13.040
Niki was, how to say,
a busy man at the time.

00:45:13.559 --> 00:45:16.328
Everyone wanted his attention.

00:45:16.540 --> 00:45:20.020
Everyone hoped he’d give
them five minutes.

00:45:20.620 --> 00:45:23.940
He came and went.
Then Goran came.

00:45:27.940 --> 00:45:34.100
Goran was preparing for his
champion run at Wimbledon in 2001.

00:45:35.500 --> 00:45:39.159
I think that moment defined things...
Niki had already accepted me.

00:45:39.438 --> 00:45:41.838
I’d been training there a while.

00:45:42.283 --> 00:45:46.523
He already saw me
as talented, and so on.

00:45:47.220 --> 00:45:54.500
But I think, when he saw
how I handled Goran on court,

00:45:54.740 --> 00:46:00.940
what I did, he said: this kid really
has something, a spark, a switch,

00:46:01.140 --> 00:46:05.700
that’s different. Not just talent,
but champion mentality.

00:46:05.830 --> 00:46:09.110
A little different from the others.
-You didn’t miss a shot...

00:46:09.399 --> 00:46:13.119
Not a single shot against Goran.
-That’s impossible.

00:46:13.392 --> 00:46:19.312
I entered some kind of zone,
an out-of-body experience with Goran,

00:46:19.780 --> 00:46:26.740
who was, of course, my childhood idol.
When he showed up, I was drooling.

00:46:27.020 --> 00:46:30.460
Then I asked Niki, can I...

00:46:30.660 --> 00:46:34.220
Whenever he's on the court,
I'm there, just to watch.

00:46:34.500 --> 00:46:38.540
He says OK, asked Goran.
He said sure. I sat there.

00:46:38.780 --> 00:46:42.540
I said, Goran, can we play?
We played. Then he...

00:46:43.020 --> 00:46:46.500
That was interesting to me.
At that moment I really didn’t plan it.

00:46:46.740 --> 00:46:52.020
But it comes from Jelena Genčić,
what I just did. So, he runs...

00:46:52.300 --> 00:46:58.020
Jelena Genčić always warned me
to stretch before and after,

00:46:58.300 --> 00:47:03.900
to warm up properly. That I had to
carry not just a spare shirt,

00:47:04.140 --> 00:47:08.620
underwear, socks, a towel,
but also a banana, Bonžita,

00:47:09.060 --> 00:47:13.140
or something sweet to have with me.

00:47:13.460 --> 00:47:17.380
To eat right away and replenish
what I lost, then go for lunch

00:47:17.620 --> 00:47:20.300
and everything else.
You need enough water,

00:47:20.580 --> 00:47:23.772
to calculate how much to sip,
how much to save.

00:47:24.043 --> 00:47:27.960
I knew all that at nine years old.
Everything was by the book.

00:47:28.578 --> 00:47:35.397
And then, I watch Goran
running after practice.

00:47:36.060 --> 00:47:41.380
I think, Goran came to train,
I saw him in the gym,

00:47:41.660 --> 00:47:45.700
didn’t see him eat anything there.
He played tennis, finished training,

00:47:45.940 --> 00:47:50.459
it lasted an hour and a half, two,
I don’t know. I didn’t see him eat anything.

00:47:50.688 --> 00:47:54.896
He drank. Played with me, now runs,
and while he waits for food

00:47:55.098 --> 00:47:58.467
to be served at the restaurant,
I'll bring him a Bonžita.

00:47:58.778 --> 00:48:05.701
I grab mine and run to him.
A kid, I was 13-14 years old,

00:48:06.089 --> 00:48:09.929
I run to Goran. Even though we played,
there were 20 kids there,

00:48:10.193 --> 00:48:14.793
what can I tell Goran,
that he needs to watch his nutrition?

00:48:15.041 --> 00:48:20.870
But I dared, and said:
"Goran, please, you haven’t eaten."

00:48:21.291 --> 00:48:26.034
"Take this, it’s good." He laughed
and said, "Alright, kid, fine."

00:48:26.700 --> 00:48:31.540
Then he told Niki, this little guy,
he brought me Bonžita.

00:48:31.860 --> 00:48:34.980
Those are the moments that...

00:48:35.540 --> 00:48:40.940
I remember them with great joy
and happiness in my heart.

00:48:41.180 --> 00:48:48.300
Every moment I spent at Pilić's
academy was perfect for me.

00:48:48.620 --> 00:48:53.060
Between ages 12 and 16,
I spent a lot of time there.

00:48:53.940 --> 00:49:00.140
Often, at times, I was maybe even alone
at the academy, when it was struggling

00:49:01.140 --> 00:49:04.780
and there weren’t many players.
I stayed out of gratitude

00:49:05.060 --> 00:49:10.420
toward Niki and everything he did.
I don’t know, Niki is my tennis father.

00:49:10.660 --> 00:49:12.900
If Jelena Genčić is the mother,
he is the father. -You said that,

00:49:13.220 --> 00:49:20.100
but you also placed on yourself...
Niki Pilić said, he mentions your winning

00:49:20.340 --> 00:49:25.900
your first Challenger in Aachen,
2004, right? -Yes.

00:49:28.260 --> 00:49:32.980
You won eight matches.
Three in qualifications and five more.

00:49:33.260 --> 00:49:38.340
Your father arrives... The prize
was about 7,500 dollars.

00:49:38.740 --> 00:49:43.820
Your father arrives and says:
"Congrats, Nole." You say: "Dad,

00:49:44.100 --> 00:49:46.420
we agreed on when
you'd congratulate me."

00:49:46.660 --> 00:49:51.500
That is... -Yes. -That’s the goal,
and all these are...

00:49:51.700 --> 00:49:54.260
Stops along the way.
-Stops along the way, but...

00:49:55.754 --> 00:50:01.354
﻿Your success isn't sudden,
because you were already

00:50:01.454 --> 00:50:04.614
a triple European champion
at the age of 14.

00:50:04.799 --> 00:50:06.876
However, as you yourself say,
and it's true,

00:50:06.991 --> 00:50:10.913
I know it from many examples,
things have to open up for you,

00:50:11.147 --> 00:50:13.772
you have to have a bit of luck too.
-Yes, 100%.

00:50:13.970 --> 00:50:15.616
And you said that yourself.

00:50:15.859 --> 00:50:18.335
That's how it is in sports
and in anything else. -That's right.

00:50:18.470 --> 00:50:21.399
That opportunity you mentioned:
"I have to take it."

00:50:22.698 --> 00:50:29.750
I asked the same thing to Karabatić, Goran,
and Željko, and now I'm asking you:

00:50:30.136 --> 00:50:33.176
What were the crossroads
where you made

00:50:33.307 --> 00:50:38.667
the right decision that launched you?
-That's a good question.

00:50:39.980 --> 00:50:52.220
Well, there were a few key moments.
I’d single out, for example, one instance...

00:50:52.660 --> 00:50:56.020
America. The first time
I went to America.

00:50:56.500 --> 00:51:01.260
I was maybe 15 and a half,
almost 16.

00:51:02.460 --> 00:51:06.940
My father and I were supposed to go
to the biggest tournaments

00:51:07.032 --> 00:51:11.272
in the world for that age group.
16 and 18 years old.

00:51:11.418 --> 00:51:13.658
That means the Prince Cup,
Orange Bowl, etc.

00:51:13.795 --> 00:51:15.515
That’s over there in Florida.

00:51:17.660 --> 00:51:21.500
We had never been to America before,
we were coming from Serbia,

00:51:21.623 --> 00:51:24.063
which doesn’t have
the best reputation over there,

00:51:24.234 --> 00:51:26.994
then there’s the visa,
the issues, the approach...

00:51:27.500 --> 00:51:30.620
I skipped many tournaments
in the junior category,

00:51:30.860 --> 00:51:34.100
because there was no money.
We simply couldn’t travel, and that’s it.

00:51:34.300 --> 00:51:38.999
When my father couldn’t afford it,
the club would help out a little,

00:51:39.243 --> 00:51:43.952
the federation - barely.
There just wasn’t any money.

00:51:44.278 --> 00:51:51.960
So for such a big venture,
the trip to America for both him and me,

00:51:52.129 --> 00:51:54.209
he had to set aside...

00:51:54.399 --> 00:52:00.929
I think at that time,
for the stay and the travel,

00:52:01.095 --> 00:52:05.055
it cost around $5.000 in total.

00:52:06.340 --> 00:52:11.950
We needed that amount just to be sure
we’d be able to stay there.

00:52:14.500 --> 00:52:22.660
At that time, finding that kind of money
was almost impossible.

00:52:23.220 --> 00:52:26.820
He told that story,
I won’t quote him now...

00:52:27.020 --> 00:52:33.220
In short, he went to those
notorious loan sharks, criminals,

00:52:33.398 --> 00:52:36.878
who were the only ones
who could lend you money

00:52:37.039 --> 00:52:40.066
just like that, but with interest.
Then comes that well-known story.

00:52:40.325 --> 00:52:46.060
He went and told them how
much money he needed and why.

00:52:47.729 --> 00:52:51.255
They asked him if he was
in a hurry, and he replied:

00:52:51.466 --> 00:52:56.016
"Yes, I’m in a hurry, we need to
leave soon because of the schedule."

00:52:56.321 --> 00:53:02.587
"Well then, the interest is 15-20%,
but since you’re in a hurry, it’ll be 30%."

00:53:04.111 --> 00:53:08.477
What could he do? He gritted his teeth,
reached out his hand and said:

00:53:08.613 --> 00:53:11.213
"Alright then, let it be what it will.

00:53:11.359 --> 00:53:13.759
I’ll find a way to get the money
and pay it back."

00:53:13.905 --> 00:53:17.825
Those were hard times, and there are
a lot of stories from back then

00:53:17.939 --> 00:53:19.619
that aren’t for the public.

00:53:19.796 --> 00:53:22.756
There was some car chasing
involved and a lot more,

00:53:22.981 --> 00:53:27.969
where he was trying to find
a way out of that trouble.

00:53:28.133 --> 00:53:30.653
In the end, he managed
to pay everything back.

00:53:30.793 --> 00:53:33.391
But I think, those were
really tough times.

00:53:33.575 --> 00:53:36.813
Even though I didn’t know about it
back then, because he hid it from me.

00:53:36.956 --> 00:53:38.923
They hid it from you.

00:53:39.175 --> 00:53:42.790
But the reason I wanted to highlight
that moment is this...

00:53:43.405 --> 00:53:48.285
When we pulled it off - actually,
when he managed to sort everything out

00:53:48.533 --> 00:53:50.693
and secure it,
then we went to America.

00:53:50.972 --> 00:53:54.052
We didn’t go to America
just for the tournaments.

00:53:54.331 --> 00:53:58.851
I think the main reason we went
was because IMG had invited us.

00:53:59.075 --> 00:54:02.435
IMG is the biggest management
agency in tennis,

00:54:02.659 --> 00:54:04.993
and one of the biggest
in all of sports.

00:54:05.386 --> 00:54:10.071
At that time, Monica Seleš was with them,
they had the best players,

00:54:10.345 --> 00:54:13.524
and in every generation,
they picked the top talents.

00:54:15.300 --> 00:54:19.620
Back then, we didn’t have
mobile phones,

00:54:20.020 --> 00:54:24.140
just a number we were supposed
to call in Tampa, Florida.

00:54:24.285 --> 00:54:27.645
We changed five planes on the way there,
and the trip took two days.

00:54:27.776 --> 00:54:30.530
There was supposed to be a man
waiting for us there,

00:54:30.648 --> 00:54:32.960
someone who had been
described to us.

00:54:33.136 --> 00:54:36.410
I won’t name him,
because he’s still on the tour.

00:54:36.591 --> 00:54:39.280
That man was supposed
to wait for the manager,

00:54:39.390 --> 00:54:41.630
and we were supposed
to arrive in the evening.

00:54:41.812 --> 00:54:44.282
He was supposed to take us
from the airport to Bradenton

00:54:44.476 --> 00:54:47.468
and arrange accommodation
at the Academy.

00:54:47.664 --> 00:54:50.464
My father didn’t know
a word of English.

00:54:51.180 --> 00:54:56.500
I knew a little,
but it was just basic level.

00:54:56.647 --> 00:54:58.854
The crucial thing was that
he wasn’t at the airport.

00:54:58.973 --> 00:55:01.151
We called, but no one answered.

00:55:03.300 --> 00:55:06.700
We had an address,
but we didn’t know if we should

00:55:06.980 --> 00:55:10.100
go there so late
or wait until the next morning.

00:55:10.368 --> 00:55:14.611
In the end, we didn’t go,
well, actually, we did,

00:55:14.752 --> 00:55:17.588
but we just "kissed the door",
because everything was locked.

00:55:17.695 --> 00:55:21.213
We ended up in a two-star motel
nearby that we found.

00:55:21.392 --> 00:55:25.533
We just slept there and showed up
there in the morning.

00:55:25.691 --> 00:55:31.299
They explained the situation to us
with the phrase: "That’s life."

00:55:32.180 --> 00:55:37.100
But you didn’t keep the agreement...
"That’s life..."

00:55:37.780 --> 00:55:43.500
That’s why my father breaks out in hives
when he hears that: "That’s life."

00:55:43.661 --> 00:55:46.030
Because it left him with
an incredible trauma.

00:55:46.092 --> 00:55:48.812
I’ve traveled half the world,
and you tell me: That’s life.

00:55:49.860 --> 00:55:52.180
That really annoyed him.

00:55:54.100 --> 00:55:59.370
At that moment, we realized
what the tennis world

00:55:59.628 --> 00:56:05.100
was like there and what a machine it was.
In the end, we managed to arrange

00:56:05.340 --> 00:56:09.020
a meeting with those people,
with the main managers.

00:56:09.220 --> 00:56:15.482
One of them was Monica Seleš’s manager.
We talked to them about everything.

00:56:16.303 --> 00:56:20.419
They promised us castles and cities,
because in the meantime,

00:56:21.100 --> 00:56:25.020
they had seen how I played,
and I had won the Prince Cup.

00:56:26.100 --> 00:56:29.700
When I came to the second Orange Bowl
for the under 18 category,

00:56:29.900 --> 00:56:31.660
after winning the previous one
for under 16,

00:56:31.900 --> 00:56:33.900
I dominated and played great.

00:56:34.144 --> 00:56:37.424
They said I had everything,
the game and the results,

00:56:37.702 --> 00:56:40.582
and that they would do everything...

00:56:41.020 --> 00:56:44.900
My father said: "Alright,
all of this sounds wonderful."

00:56:45.140 --> 00:56:51.020
He was always careful, because life
taught him not to jump in headfirst.

00:56:51.260 --> 00:56:55.180
He wasn’t especially trusting,
thanks to that first day,

00:56:55.471 --> 00:57:01.193
but at the second meeting,
all of it sounded good to him,

00:57:01.365 --> 00:57:05.020
so he told me: "Son, this is great.

00:57:05.500 --> 00:57:08.460
You’ll have money
and a place to stay,

00:57:08.660 --> 00:57:11.700
you’ll have a base here
and a base in Europe."

00:57:12.140 --> 00:57:15.460
I think that’s the reason
why it all fell apart.

00:57:16.660 --> 00:57:19.392
Because they usually bring
the whole world there with them,

00:57:19.541 --> 00:57:21.790
and you’re based there,
and entire families have to

00:57:21.910 --> 00:57:23.306
move there as well.

00:57:23.432 --> 00:57:26.558
Like you said, I don’t know if it’s
the same in other sports.

00:57:26.728 --> 00:57:29.175
I assume it is,
based on conversations

00:57:29.526 --> 00:57:32.166
with some fantastic footballers,
who were and still are.

00:57:32.435 --> 00:57:35.416
They told me that when you come
from a small country,

00:57:35.717 --> 00:57:38.745
they usually find you a job,
for example, in London,

00:57:38.894 --> 00:57:41.245
a house, and so on, they provide
for your whole family

00:57:41.360 --> 00:57:44.753
so you can be there
at the Chelsea Academy or wherever.

00:57:44.902 --> 00:57:47.839
The family is with you, you grow up,
and have a normal childhood. -Yes.

00:57:47.922 --> 00:57:50.802
But it’s a big step for the whole family
to move to another country

00:57:50.916 --> 00:57:53.392
whose language they
don’t even know.

00:57:53.482 --> 00:57:56.900
But in most cases, you go to
a "better country." Whatever that means.

00:57:57.023 --> 00:57:59.246
I understand,
better in terms of conditions.

00:57:59.391 --> 00:58:01.391
Economically better, because
you’ll have a higher salary,

00:58:01.569 --> 00:58:04.136
a better house, and many other things.
-Yes. That’s normal.

00:58:04.294 --> 00:58:07.214
But again, I say,
what was important for him

00:58:07.384 --> 00:58:12.266
was what Niki told us,
considering that I was still with him...

00:58:13.298 --> 00:58:16.258
Niki told us: "Alright, go ahead,
but my advice is

00:58:16.366 --> 00:58:18.565
that you don’t have to go to them."

00:58:18.706 --> 00:58:22.534
"Go play tournaments,
but they won’t give you anything."

00:58:23.300 --> 00:58:29.734
My father didn’t say anything to Niki
the first time, he just looked at him,

00:58:29.909 --> 00:58:34.312
but later he told me: "I don’t
understand why he’s saying this.

00:58:34.373 --> 00:58:36.499
How can they not give us anything?

00:58:36.634 --> 00:58:39.101
You’re the best in the world
in that category."

00:58:39.235 --> 00:58:41.755
They’re supposed to give you money,
and help financially

00:58:41.916 --> 00:58:45.617
and with management, provide knowledge,
conditions, coaches, etc.,

00:58:45.694 --> 00:58:47.749
because we were open to all of that.

00:58:47.868 --> 00:58:50.388
Niki said: "Yes, go ahead,
because you need that.

00:58:50.479 --> 00:58:52.930
I can give you this here,
but for all the rest,

00:58:53.101 --> 00:58:59.202
for travel, for the coaching staff, etc.,
for that you need someone like them."

00:58:59.456 --> 00:59:03.016
But he added: "Knowing them
and my experience with them...

00:59:03.425 --> 00:59:07.265
And because you’re from Serbia
and a million other things."

00:59:07.551 --> 00:59:14.086
I was a kid and didn’t want to think
that Niki wasn’t right.

00:59:14.273 --> 00:59:19.594
But I can see that my father
didn’t really like what Niki said.

00:59:19.740 --> 00:59:23.740
He didn’t fully believe him
at that moment,

00:59:23.839 --> 00:59:26.799
even though he trusted him
unconditionally in everything else.

00:59:26.890 --> 00:59:30.010
It was as if he didn’t believe
that would happen,

00:59:30.106 --> 00:59:32.145
but that the opposite would happen.

00:59:32.288 --> 00:59:34.688
And after two meetings,
that’s exactly how it was.

00:59:34.818 --> 00:59:37.698
They offered us all of that,
"castles and cities" and everything.

00:59:37.882 --> 00:59:43.826
Niki warned us then:
"If they promise you everything,

00:59:44.022 --> 00:59:49.842
which I doubt, say that you want
to have a base in Europe as well."

00:59:50.156 --> 00:59:53.516
That means you have a base with them,
but when you’re in Europe

00:59:53.613 --> 00:59:55.733
for European tournaments
for several months,

00:59:55.823 --> 00:59:57.709
you need a European base.

00:59:57.858 --> 01:00:02.739
You can be in Serbia, at my academy
or wherever you decide,

01:00:02.895 --> 01:00:08.023
but you need a base from which you go
and where you have an organized life.

01:00:08.500 --> 01:00:12.140
Which is logical, normal, and expected.
When we asked for that, they said

01:00:12.277 --> 01:00:15.405
there was no problem
and it made sense.

01:00:15.532 --> 01:00:18.764
They said they would get back to us
in a few days after we returned.

01:00:18.937 --> 01:00:21.937
They never got back to us.
-Never? -They never got back.

01:00:22.153 --> 01:00:27.193
Even to this day, when we see them,
because I see them at tournaments,

01:00:27.620 --> 01:00:30.220
I greet them and so on.

01:00:30.500 --> 01:00:35.166
That’s the world where things
happen and unfold that way.

01:00:36.534 --> 01:00:40.854
We realized that we came
from a different mentality.

01:00:41.761 --> 01:00:43.471
I’m speaking generally.

01:00:43.585 --> 01:00:45.845
I’m not claiming that everyone
from this region is like that.

01:00:45.931 --> 01:00:48.223
But generally, we are like that,
all the people from the countries

01:00:48.317 --> 01:00:50.197
of the former Yugoslavia.

01:00:50.328 --> 01:00:54.393
Our word means more than paper,
and that has value.

01:00:56.647 --> 01:01:01.041
When you tell someone something,
make a promise, shake hands,

01:01:01.168 --> 01:01:04.534
look them in the eye and say it’s so,
and then stab them in the back...

01:01:04.564 --> 01:01:05.994
We can’t understand that.

01:01:06.066 --> 01:01:08.268
We couldn’t understand it
for a long time.

01:01:08.366 --> 01:01:11.514
Because of that, my father suffered a lot,
because he couldn’t understand

01:01:11.609 --> 01:01:13.474
why it was like that.

01:01:14.180 --> 01:01:17.662
But for them, it seems,
that’s everyday life - that’s normal.

01:01:17.849 --> 01:01:20.444
Unless you put something on paper,
then it’s something else.

01:01:20.549 --> 01:01:23.193
But you know that yourself,
you spent so many years there.

01:01:23.354 --> 01:01:25.780
Yes, for them, it’s all business,
nothing personal.

01:01:25.927 --> 01:01:29.014
And for us, it’s all personal,
and nothing business...

01:01:29.356 --> 01:01:32.396
Aren’t you ashamed
of your parents and everything?

01:01:32.583 --> 01:01:35.223
And it’s good that it’s that way.

01:01:35.537 --> 01:01:40.442
I somehow grew up
with that kind of value system -

01:01:40.918 --> 01:01:42.903
to see a person as a person.

01:01:43.096 --> 01:01:45.456
You and I, for example,
do some business, whatever it is.

01:01:45.570 --> 01:01:48.192
You have a project, or we’re working
on something in sports, whatever.

01:01:48.373 --> 01:01:51.520
And that’s all fine.
We’ll put some things on paper,

01:01:51.672 --> 01:01:57.352
protect you, protect me, our business,
and organize it all properly.

01:01:57.980 --> 01:02:02.540
But you and I - if we don’t understand
each other in terms of values, meaning,

01:02:02.740 --> 01:02:08.740
if we can’t, how should I say,
cohesively understand each other as people...

01:02:08.940 --> 01:02:14.351
And that’s different in the West.
-Over there, it’s all competition.

01:02:15.202 --> 01:02:18.153
Alright. Let’s get back to tennis a bit.

01:02:21.744 --> 01:02:26.384
So, the jump from juniors to seniors
happened. This interests me...

01:02:27.820 --> 01:02:33.580
Your first big tournament was
Australia 2008, right?

01:02:34.940 --> 01:02:39.620
After that, you said
that in the next two years

01:02:42.540 --> 01:02:45.540
you established yourself as third,
but couldn’t find a way

01:02:45.860 --> 01:02:51.700
to win the important matches
against Federer and Nadal.

01:02:52.460 --> 01:02:56.540
And you emphasize winning
the Davis Cup in 2010

01:02:56.780 --> 01:03:02.460
as the moment that
made that possible. - Yes.

01:03:02.660 --> 01:03:09.580
Was that the end of some maturing process,
or did you need that one push,

01:03:09.820 --> 01:03:14.340
that achievement to convince yourself
and say: "I can do this"?

01:03:14.540 --> 01:03:16.220
I think it’s the latter.

01:03:16.420 --> 01:03:23.740
I needed that springboard.
Because in 2007, I won Miami,

01:03:24.180 --> 01:03:26.420
I won Montreal,
and those are big tournaments -

01:03:26.620 --> 01:03:28.740
the biggest after the Grand Slams.

01:03:28.980 --> 01:03:32.540
And there, I already felt
that I belonged at the top.

01:03:32.740 --> 01:03:37.100
I was already third in the world then,
behind those two.

01:03:38.140 --> 01:03:42.260
And then came the first Grand Slam -
the Australian Open -

01:03:44.060 --> 01:03:48.980
and somehow there,
as a twenty-year-old, young,

01:03:49.180 --> 01:03:52.220
I won the Grand Slam
and wrote my name in golden letters

01:03:52.460 --> 01:03:54.340
in the history of our sport.

01:03:54.540 --> 01:03:57.740
Because as a Grand Slam winner,
you are, in a way, immortal.

01:03:57.980 --> 01:04:02.180
But that didn’t satisfy me -
it wasn’t enough.

01:04:02.900 --> 01:04:07.140
First of all, I wanted Wimbledon,
because that was the dream tournament,

01:04:07.340 --> 01:04:11.660
the one I dreamed about,
the one that motivated me as a kid.

01:04:11.860 --> 01:04:16.740
And I also wanted to dominate
over Federer and Nadal.

01:04:18.260 --> 01:04:20.860
Because those two were
so dominant,

01:04:21.060 --> 01:04:25.100
and the contrast in their
playing styles and personalities

01:04:25.300 --> 01:04:32.180
made a perfect Hollywood story.
-Yes. -Their rivalry.

01:04:32.414 --> 01:04:34.555
And then I showed up.

01:04:34.648 --> 01:04:37.040
"What are you doing here?
There’s no room for a third."

01:04:37.307 --> 01:04:43.962
You come from Serbia - skinny,
small - and you’re also arrogant,

01:04:44.118 --> 01:04:48.758
saying you can be No. 1. -Yes.
-And then when I won that,

01:04:51.100 --> 01:04:59.580
I broke the ice, but then I felt
what everyone feels

01:04:59.820 --> 01:05:02.460
when they win their
first Grand Slam,

01:05:02.660 --> 01:05:05.860
without knowing
what that feeling really means.

01:05:06.060 --> 01:05:09.900
And that’s what it means to be
a Grand Slam winner -

01:05:10.140 --> 01:05:13.500
or the defending Grand Slam champion -
for the first time.

01:05:13.780 --> 01:05:17.661
It brings a lot of beautiful things.
As I said, it’s a relief,

01:05:17.825 --> 01:05:20.945
you’ve dreamed about it your whole life...

01:05:21.620 --> 01:05:24.900
But suddenly, all eyes are on you,
and suddenly,

01:05:25.140 --> 01:05:29.900
you are one of the main favorites
wherever you play, whatever you do.

01:05:30.820 --> 01:05:35.300
Then begins the creation
of a certain kind of pressure -

01:05:35.700 --> 01:05:38.580
a type of pressure
you haven’t faced before.

01:05:38.780 --> 01:05:40.980
I did have those pressures
we talked about,

01:05:41.220 --> 01:05:43.380
but this was something new.

01:05:43.620 --> 01:05:47.380
Suddenly, I’m no longer just attacking -
now I’m also defending.

01:05:47.620 --> 01:05:50.980
Before, I was just attacking,
winning, climbing.

01:05:51.780 --> 01:05:57.140
Now the expectations are...
If he doesn’t win the title, it’s a failure.

01:05:58.260 --> 01:06:02.140
You get a bit defensive.
You tighten up.

01:06:03.060 --> 01:06:07.100
I didn't win a Grand Slam
for three years until 2011.

01:06:07.460 --> 01:06:12.180
The second one was that Australian
Open, I think it was in 2010.

01:06:12.900 --> 01:06:16.220
I changed my racket that year.

01:06:16.940 --> 01:06:20.446
I had an injury.
And I was searching for myself...

01:06:20.616 --> 01:06:25.501
I changed some team members.
My serve mechanics were off.

01:06:27.246 --> 01:06:30.329
Searching, what, how,
this and that...

01:06:30.609 --> 01:06:35.929
I went through a lot of difficulties.
Really, I didn't feel myself.

01:06:36.380 --> 01:06:38.820
I wasn’t grounded.
-And you needed that.

01:06:39.020 --> 01:06:41.649
I was still ranked third, though.

01:06:41.859 --> 01:06:44.499
I still had a great career
and good results,

01:06:44.746 --> 01:06:47.946
but for the expectations
and visions I wanted,

01:06:48.123 --> 01:06:50.683
there was something missing.

01:06:51.820 --> 01:06:57.480
And during those three years,
I was losing big matches,

01:06:58.222 --> 01:07:05.226
until the moment
I changed my habits,

01:07:05.811 --> 01:07:10.450
my diet and the way I recovered.
I felt I had more strength

01:07:10.637 --> 01:07:13.520
and I solved problems
with allergies and breathing.

01:07:13.700 --> 01:07:16.469
That was causing me
a lot of trouble on the court.

01:07:17.817 --> 01:07:21.310
But the biggest turning point
was winning the Davis Cup,

01:07:21.580 --> 01:07:24.660
here in Belgrade,
in front of a full arena.

01:07:25.060 --> 01:07:27.460
It was magnificent.

01:07:28.500 --> 01:07:31.340
That's probably something
you only experience once,

01:07:31.580 --> 01:07:34.380
and it wasn’t just for me...

01:07:34.580 --> 01:07:39.436
That was for Janko, Viktor, Nenad,
for all of us on the national team.

01:07:39.680 --> 01:07:41.560
That was a huge boost.

01:07:41.957 --> 01:07:46.366
We continued to have
our best seasons after.

01:07:46.620 --> 01:07:53.850
In 2011, I probably had
my best season ever. 43 wins...

01:07:54.718 --> 01:07:57.740
For half a year,
I didn’t lose a single match.

01:07:58.020 --> 01:08:00.220
I won three Grand Slams, etc.

01:08:00.540 --> 01:08:03.420
So that was definitely a springboard.

01:08:05.260 --> 01:08:09.460
When you talked about it,
it made you smile. Goran told me that.

01:08:09.740 --> 01:08:15.070
So, out of your three most
meaningful achievements,

01:08:15.580 --> 01:08:17.620
two were with national team.

01:08:17.900 --> 01:08:23.660
One was Wimbledon,
a dream for most tennis players,

01:08:24.100 --> 01:08:28.420
the Davis Cup
and the Olympics in 2024.

01:08:29.100 --> 01:08:33.300
Goran told me that your motivation
to play for the national team

01:08:33.540 --> 01:08:38.420
is a million times greater
than for individual events.

01:08:38.620 --> 01:08:40.620
That’s true for all of us,

01:08:40.860 --> 01:08:44.105
but I think in your sport
it’s a bit more noticeable,

01:08:44.230 --> 01:08:46.950
because in football we have
someone like Vidić or Modrić.

01:08:47.096 --> 01:08:50.918
Modrić played for Dinamo
and already built a reputation there.

01:08:51.206 --> 01:08:55.105
Vidić at Red Star,
and later at Real Madrid.

01:08:55.431 --> 01:08:58.113
You have a sense of belonging
at Manchester United.

01:08:58.344 --> 01:09:01.894
You have your locker room,
your club, your fans,

01:09:02.261 --> 01:09:06.199
but you don’t have that here.
There’s no club in Serbia for you.

01:09:06.405 --> 01:09:08.725
There is a club, technically,
but no matches. -None.

01:09:08.863 --> 01:09:10.863
There are no home matches.
-That's right.

01:09:11.027 --> 01:09:19.721
And because of that, you feel even more
motivated to give something to the fans.

01:09:19.893 --> 01:09:26.093
True. In football, basketball,
and team sports,

01:09:26.580 --> 01:09:31.220
there are always some
competitions going on.

01:09:31.460 --> 01:09:35.220
Not just because they’re team sports,
but also for the national team.

01:09:35.494 --> 01:09:38.773
You have your audience,
not club-based, but national team.

01:09:39.023 --> 01:09:41.183
Especially now that
they’ve extended the season:

01:09:41.423 --> 01:09:44.685
Nations League, then World Cup
and European qualifiers.

01:09:44.905 --> 01:09:47.065
Every year there's something.

01:09:47.220 --> 01:09:52.942
There’s always some gathering.
It’s nice to see that,

01:09:53.161 --> 01:09:57.500
but I’m also a bit envious when
they meet every month or two.

01:09:57.860 --> 01:10:00.540
They all show up in their tracksuits,

01:10:00.780 --> 01:10:03.660
hang out together during
the training camp,

01:10:03.900 --> 01:10:07.140
they play one or two matches
in front of their home crowd.

01:10:07.391 --> 01:10:09.431
That’s truly a great feeling.

01:10:09.702 --> 01:10:12.262
I miss playing more
in my own country.

01:10:12.393 --> 01:10:18.673
I feel that connection,
not just with the people of Serbia,

01:10:19.140 --> 01:10:23.940
but also with the people from
the other countries of Yugoslavia.

01:10:24.380 --> 01:10:28.780
Somehow, I feel love
and that sense of belonging,

01:10:29.053 --> 01:10:31.773
a desire and passion
to perform in front of them.

01:10:32.036 --> 01:10:35.076
I’d love to do that,
but I don’t have the opportunity.

01:10:35.900 --> 01:10:40.220
One of the things I’d love to do,
if there’s no official tournament,

01:10:40.485 --> 01:10:45.205
is to organize one. I’ve even
spoken with Čila about it.

01:10:45.500 --> 01:10:48.420
At one point, during COVID,
the Adria Tour had the idea

01:10:48.700 --> 01:10:56.915
to organize a kind of
exhibition tournament,

01:10:57.086 --> 01:10:59.126
in the countries of former Yugoslavia.

01:10:59.423 --> 01:11:04.095
To play and promote the sport
for humanitarian purposes.

01:11:04.372 --> 01:11:08.532
That’s beautiful.
We really enjoy doing that.

01:11:08.673 --> 01:11:12.774
But it’s hard to align the schedule,
but we will do it one day.

01:11:14.522 --> 01:11:19.802
Yes, in our sport, that feeling is
even stronger, for all these reasons,

01:11:22.740 --> 01:11:28.100
but we rarely have the chance.
You mentioned the Olympics?

01:11:28.340 --> 01:11:33.500
The Olympics really are
my greatest achievement.

01:11:33.860 --> 01:11:37.060
When I think about it,
it depends on the perspective.

01:11:37.380 --> 01:11:40.420
I see it from the strength of emotion.
To me, that’s everything in life.

01:11:42.420 --> 01:11:47.180
You can talk about achievements,
tournaments, goals,

01:11:47.820 --> 01:11:53.660
but when you say something,
it makes your emotions tremble,

01:11:54.032 --> 01:11:58.580
you tremble, that’s it.
Do you understand me?

01:12:00.540 --> 01:12:03.141
When I mention the Olympics
that was last year,

01:12:03.281 --> 01:12:05.530
my hands start to sweat and I shake.

01:12:06.245 --> 01:12:11.219
I also trembled during the defeats
that I had at the Olympics.

01:12:11.580 --> 01:12:13.660
Because those were the biggest
losses of my career,

01:12:13.940 --> 01:12:24.198
the most painful, the most emotional.
-Is that why your Olympic career... -Yes.

01:12:24.703 --> 01:12:30.343
You’ve won everything, but it was
turbulent. -Yes. -Since 2008.

01:12:30.513 --> 01:12:33.167
I had to wait five Olympics
for that moment.

01:12:33.354 --> 01:12:37.495
Isn’t that an enormous pressure
knowing you want to do it,

01:12:37.632 --> 01:12:40.182
and knowing how rare the chance is?

01:12:40.438 --> 01:12:47.198
You don’t wait a year or a few months,
you wait four years for the next one.

01:12:47.944 --> 01:12:49.599
What kind of desire is that?

01:12:49.762 --> 01:12:54.242
And you said that after
all those turbulent moments,

01:12:54.735 --> 01:13:00.468
you changed something after Rio?
Your approach to Tokyo? -Yes.

01:13:00.581 --> 01:13:03.101
What can you change?

01:13:04.740 --> 01:13:07.820
I was very close to that
medal in Tokyo.

01:13:09.500 --> 01:13:13.420
At that time, I was maybe having
the second-best season of my career.

01:13:13.628 --> 01:13:17.197
Maybe even the best, 2021.
That was during COVID,

01:13:17.329 --> 01:13:20.103
and the matches were played
without spectators, remember?

01:13:23.180 --> 01:13:27.780
The entire Olympic experience
wasn't the usual one.

01:13:28.060 --> 01:13:30.700
But still, it was the Olympics.

01:13:30.948 --> 01:13:34.228
Even if you're playing in front
of empty stands, it's your sport.

01:13:34.540 --> 01:13:41.665
And people from different countries
are watching you. It still holds meaning.

01:13:44.860 --> 01:13:48.820
In Beijing, during my first Olympics,
I won the bronze medal.

01:13:49.060 --> 01:13:58.180
I had a very close match with Nadal,
which I lost and then I won the bronze.

01:13:59.540 --> 01:14:02.060
In London, I made it
to the semifinals as well.

01:14:02.190 --> 01:14:04.310
I’ve always played well at the Olympics.

01:14:04.456 --> 01:14:07.421
But I just couldn’t get past
the semifinals.

01:14:07.726 --> 01:14:10.780
And it’s really interesting
how all that played out.

01:14:11.060 --> 01:14:15.260
In 2012, I played against
Andy Murray at Wimbledon.

01:14:16.140 --> 01:14:20.737
I lost a very tight match in two sets.
I had so many chances.

01:14:21.140 --> 01:14:26.100
If I could go back,
I’d replay those matches.

01:14:26.780 --> 01:14:30.220
And again, I lost to Del Potro
on another court.

01:14:30.460 --> 01:14:32.820
Same thing, interruptions,
rain, and so on...

01:14:32.996 --> 01:14:36.382
but I had already won bronze
and was fighting for it again.

01:14:36.566 --> 01:14:39.126
I wanted to win,
but I was emotionally drained

01:14:39.264 --> 01:14:42.327
from the loss the day before
and it was really hard to get going.

01:14:43.580 --> 01:14:47.220
I experienced that twice:
in London and in Tokyo.

01:14:47.580 --> 01:14:54.436
In Rio, I was probably
at the absolute peak of my career.

01:14:56.456 --> 01:15:01.241
I had, for a year and a half,
the best results of my life.

01:15:01.470 --> 01:15:06.038
At that point, I had all four
Grand Slam titles in a row.

01:15:06.830 --> 01:15:09.030
It doesn’t get better than that.

01:15:09.194 --> 01:15:13.670
I came to Rio four days early.

01:15:15.820 --> 01:15:22.420
The conditions I trained in were
perfect, thank God. Ideal for me.

01:15:22.780 --> 01:15:27.540
Bounce, balls, speed, air,
everything was perfect.

01:15:29.620 --> 01:15:31.740
I was training fantastically.

01:15:31.902 --> 01:15:34.862
Playing those practice matches,
crushing everyone left and right.

01:15:35.070 --> 01:15:38.254
Then comes the day before the match.

01:15:38.407 --> 01:15:41.098
I’m playing singles, and I’m
also preparing for doubles,

01:15:41.229 --> 01:15:43.389
because I was playing
doubles with Zimonjić.

01:15:43.500 --> 01:15:46.272
I play that singles practice
match for two hours.

01:15:46.398 --> 01:15:49.663
And I think I'll do two more
hours of doubles. So I play that too.

01:15:49.851 --> 01:15:53.891
I finish, and then my wrist
starts to hurt.

01:15:54.085 --> 01:15:59.311
I think it’s just from overuse
and the balls. Just a little fatigue.

01:15:59.438 --> 01:16:01.999
Then the physio takes a look at it.

01:16:02.149 --> 01:16:04.815
Next morning, I wake up
and I can’t move my wrist.

01:16:06.402 --> 01:16:10.494
One day before the match.
What do I do? Shock!

01:16:11.241 --> 01:16:18.625
I get injections and every possible
pill. And I go out and play.

01:16:19.046 --> 01:16:24.218
But it wasn’t right.
I couldn’t do my backhand.

01:16:25.073 --> 01:16:28.873
I played an okay match,
and I don’t want to take anything away

01:16:28.964 --> 01:16:31.332
from Del Potro, who beat me
in the first round.

01:16:31.457 --> 01:16:36.130
I had a very tough draw, and he ended up
winning the silver for Argentina.

01:16:36.290 --> 01:16:40.137
But for me, that might be
the most painful loss.

01:16:40.301 --> 01:16:44.411
Given the moment I was in,
and how everything was unfolding...

01:16:45.100 --> 01:16:49.100
Then we move forward five years.
2021, Tokyo.

01:16:50.220 --> 01:16:54.700
I changed my approach. I didn’t
stay in the Olympic Village.

01:16:57.660 --> 01:17:02.460
One of the things that fascinates me
is that I always wanted to attend

01:17:02.660 --> 01:17:06.020
the opening ceremony of Olympic Games.

01:17:06.580 --> 01:17:12.220
But those ceremonies involve standing
for five to six hours, waiting...

01:17:12.460 --> 01:17:17.340
And we would usually play the next day,
on day one of the Olympic Games.

01:17:18.740 --> 01:17:24.220
So it didn’t make much sense. You need
rested legs, your body, your spine.

01:17:25.700 --> 01:17:29.260
And even though it was tough
for me, I said, I’ll skip it.

01:17:29.460 --> 01:17:32.260
There’s no audience, so it’ll be
easier to miss it in Tokyo.

01:17:32.537 --> 01:17:34.955
Honestly, it was worth it,
in that sense. I slept in a hotel.

01:17:35.116 --> 01:17:37.088
I went to the village during the day.

01:17:37.247 --> 01:17:39.857
My brother Marko was with me
at the Olympics.

01:17:41.060 --> 01:17:45.220
I didn’t lose a set, not even three games
per set, until the semifinal.

01:17:45.420 --> 01:17:47.980
I was playing amazing tennis.

01:17:48.180 --> 01:17:52.700
In the semifinal against Zverev.
I’m leading 6-1, 3-2, and serving.

01:17:53.300 --> 01:17:59.820
But for two days I’d been feeling
I had minimal reserves of energy.

01:18:00.220 --> 01:18:05.660
Minimal. I was praying just
to make it to the final.

01:18:06.060 --> 01:18:10.020
Because if I win, I get a rest day,
since we were playing every day.

01:18:10.260 --> 01:18:14.820
That day of rest would have
given me time to recover.

01:18:15.020 --> 01:18:18.580
And to have enough energy
to win the gold.

01:18:19.020 --> 01:18:24.357
He started playing well, and I retired
and began to doubt myself.

01:18:24.598 --> 01:18:33.751
I lost the second set, then the third,
and that was it. I had no strength left.

01:18:34.320 --> 01:18:36.735
It was really painful.

01:18:37.332 --> 01:18:45.072
As painful as it was,
it took me longer to get over it

01:18:45.534 --> 01:18:49.934
than other losses, because I felt like
it wasn’t the end.

01:18:50.294 --> 01:18:54.662
I still had Paris ahead of me,
even though I was in my thirties.

01:18:54.985 --> 01:18:58.585
I take care of my body
and I’m mentally strong.

01:18:58.934 --> 01:19:03.454
Paris is ahead of me, I’ll be ready.

01:19:06.700 --> 01:19:12.570
Now, to return to the first question...

01:19:12.900 --> 01:19:15.620
Balance, optimal goals...

01:19:15.940 --> 01:19:21.620
The only thing I currently
have in my vision...

01:19:21.900 --> 01:19:25.260
It’s interesting, when we talk about
those achievements and the Olympics,

01:19:25.327 --> 01:19:27.487
which stands out alongside
the Davis Cup,

01:19:27.601 --> 01:19:34.201
what gives me motivation is the 2028
Olympics in Los Angeles,

01:19:35.620 --> 01:19:38.100
and playing for my country.

01:19:38.222 --> 01:19:40.626
And yes, the Grand Prix
and Grand Slam tournaments,

01:19:40.765 --> 01:19:43.236
but not even they motivate me
as much as the Olympics.

01:19:43.338 --> 01:19:46.478
How I see it... -Even though
you’ve now won in Paris?

01:19:46.692 --> 01:19:50.372
I just want to be at the Olympics,
to be an Olympian.

01:19:50.619 --> 01:19:56.000
To experience that moment,
wearing my country’s crest,

01:19:56.096 --> 01:19:59.522
walking through the Olympic Village
with the world’s best athletes.

01:19:59.608 --> 01:20:01.522
That feeling is sport itself.

01:20:01.600 --> 01:20:05.260
Anyone who hasn’t experienced it
can’t fully understand it.

01:20:05.395 --> 01:20:09.939
But for athletes, who’ve had the privilege
to experience it, it’s unique.

01:20:10.325 --> 01:20:17.564
Historically, the Olympics weren’t
tied to football or tennis.

01:20:17.791 --> 01:20:23.205
It was athletics, gymnastics, swimming,
those are the Olympic sports.

01:20:23.345 --> 01:20:25.556
Or water polo and basketball.

01:20:26.106 --> 01:20:28.826
But tennis wasn’t always
connected to the Olympics.

01:20:31.260 --> 01:20:39.780
Still, you can’t help but feel
the full magic of the Olympics.

01:20:40.020 --> 01:20:43.960
For me, it’s mainly about
the Olympic Village.

01:20:44.940 --> 01:20:48.300
Besides representing your country

01:20:48.626 --> 01:20:51.142
and being in a completely
different atmosphere.

01:20:51.282 --> 01:20:54.082
Even though we play tournaments and
the Olympics was held at Roland Garros,

01:20:54.165 --> 01:20:58.158
these are completely different people,
a different organization,

01:20:58.368 --> 01:21:01.728
everything is different.
Even the balls are different.

01:21:01.865 --> 01:21:05.244
Everyone has their own protocols...
-And it’s best-of-three sets?

01:21:05.380 --> 01:21:09.340
Athletes from your country come
to watch you.

01:21:09.783 --> 01:21:13.583
And when you walk through
that Olympic Village see

01:21:13.940 --> 01:21:21.430
those 10,000-15,000 athletes
from all over the world those athletes,

01:21:21.797 --> 01:21:27.108
as you said, the original Olympic sports,
who’ve been preparing

01:21:27.234 --> 01:21:29.234
for four years just for this...

01:21:29.317 --> 01:21:33.944
We have the privilege in our sports
to play important events every year.

01:21:34.237 --> 01:21:36.749
But they wait and train
specifically for this.

01:21:37.006 --> 01:21:45.053
In their eyes you can see the hunger,
the spark, how happy they are to be there.

01:21:45.215 --> 01:21:47.455
How inspired and motivated they are.

01:21:47.703 --> 01:21:51.143
You go into the gym and work out
with them and when you watch them,

01:21:51.440 --> 01:21:56.253
you feel like you could carry the whole
world on your shoulders.

01:21:56.801 --> 01:21:59.921
Those are the things that, for me...

01:22:00.081 --> 01:22:05.481
That have always remained
my biggest motivation.

01:22:05.609 --> 01:22:07.744
The Olympics and the national team.

01:22:07.856 --> 01:22:10.862
It’s incredible how you speak,
we could talk like this for days.

01:22:16.340 --> 01:22:20.820
That concludes the first part
of the interview with Novak Đoković.

01:22:21.300 --> 01:22:25.940
Watch part two on Arena Sport
in two weeks. Goodbye!

